\title{Simulation-Based Power Analysis for Mixed-Effects Models}
\description{
\strong{mixpower} is a simulation-based toolkit for power and sample-size analysis
for linear and generalized linear mixed-effects models (LMMs and GLMMs). It is
design-first (no pilot data required), supports Gaussian, binomial, Poisson,
and negative binomial families via \strong{lme4}; Wald and likelihood-ratio tests;
multi-parameter sensitivity grids; power curves and minimum sample-size
solvers; parallel evaluation with deterministic seeds; and full
reproducibility (manifests, result bundling, export to CSV/JSON). Every run
reports diagnostics (failure rate, singular-fit rate, effective N).
}
\details{
Typical workflow: (1) define a design with \code{mp_design()} (cluster sizes,
trials per cell) and effect-size assumptions with \code{mp_assumptions()}; (2) build
a scenario with a backend constructor (e.g. \code{mp_scenario_lme4()} for Gaussian
LMM); (3) run \code{mp_power()} for a single power estimate, \code{mp_sensitivity()} to
vary parameters, or \code{mp_power_curve()} / \code{mp_solve_sample_size()} for curves
and sample-size. Use a fixed \code{seed} for reproducibility. Failure and
singular-fit rates are always reported and never suppressed.
}
